North Korea Rejects Unilateral Disarmament Without Confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions would deepen its mistrust of the United States, and under those circumstances the country would in no way unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial measures of good will” last year, for example by stopping nuclear and missile tests, demolishing the nuclear test site and committing itself not to increase nuclear weapons and technologies.
“We don’t see a response from the United States,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there is no trust in our national security, and under these circumstances we will not unilaterally disarm first.”
While Ri repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in so far as it had not initially rejected a unilateral denuclearization, as Pyeongja said.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim had assured to work toward the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump added guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, while the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington opposes demands for a easing of strict international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘first denuclearization’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through coercion, and is even against the ‘explanation of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The assumption that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a brain tease of people who don’t know anything about us.
The problem, however, is that the continued sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not go into plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the U.S. head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean head of state Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea were the other party in the denuclearization question instead of the US, it would not have come to this standstill in the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula.”
Nevertheless, the tone of Ris’ speech differed enormously from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the US mainland with North Korea’s missiles after “evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who had threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea last year, heaped praise on Kim at the United Nations for his courage in terms of disarmament steps, but said there was still much work to be done and the sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for it: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of the Security Council sanctions must definitely be vigorously continued until we have achieved complete, final and verified denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry up Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would revisit Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was not successful.
In July, on his departure from Pyongyang, he said progress had been made on being accused by North Korea just hours later of making “gangster-like demands.”
North Korea vowed at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile base and a nuclear complex if the United States took “appropriate action.”
He said Kim had told him that the “appropriate measures” he intended were security guarantees Trump had given in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn in one course to get enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University ensures that all students get more sleep this year in elementary school. This is a measure against the expanding macho culture of staying awake with caffeine and learning all night long.
One scientist has found that students at the world’s leading university are often unnecessary when it comes to paying attention to themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and is in his opinion the first such course in the United States.
He was inspired to bring the course to life after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and asked, ‘Why am I only learning about this now, in my last year?’
According to her, no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
This year’s course for the first time explained to students how the basics of good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance and also improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university chose to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see the image of a room in a residential home and click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
Then, using a map of the university campus with interactive symbols, they are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this – just as you have the right to know how the decision to smoke affects your health,” added Professor Czeisler.
The pride of pushing a “night shift” is still widespread, he said, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students make sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring enough sleep should be the “secret weapon” of all students against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said, as well as avoiding weight gain as sleep deprivation puts the brain into starvation mode so that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course. He had taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and encouraged him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step, all postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar degree program before embarking on their studies at the competitive university.
According to Professor Czeisler’s recommendation, students should set an alarm clock for sleep time and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emanating from electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm.
