Why Beijing could benefit from the US-China trade war
The opening salvos of the trade war between the US and China were deafening. Although the battle is far from over, Beijing could benefit from a trench between the countries in the long term, my experts.
Donald Trump, the U.S. president, fired the first warning shot earlier this year when he imposed punitive tariffs on key Chinese exports, including solar cells, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation this week came with new punitive tariffs on $200 billion worth of goods, effectively affecting half of all goods imported from China to the U.S.
Beijing retaliated in the same way each time and recently imposed punitive tariffs of five to ten percent on US goods worth $60 billion.
China has vowed to respond to any action by the US, and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will soon crash.
To move Washington to condescension would be to give in, but a public condescension to the United States would be far too shameful for China’s President Xi Jinping.
Nevertheless, my experts believe that if Beijing plays its cards well, China could benefit from the long-term effects of the trade war by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in either Washington or Beijing could create the conditions for economic turbulence in both countries is actually much more dangerous than many observers have previously recognized,” says Abigail Grace, a research associate who focuses on Asia at the Center for New American Security think tank.
Syria 'ready' for return of refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the country, which has been devastated by the war for over seven years.
Speaking before the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, the situation on the ground is more stable and safer,” he said.
The government is rebuilding the areas destroyed by terrorists in order to restore normalcy.
All conditions were now given for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian government would welcome help in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that it would not accept conditional aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
