Red Tide Update: Concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota Decline
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decline in red tide concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more abundant flowering conditions are recorded in the areas of the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating declining concentrations.
A red algal bloom extends over approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the south of the Lee District.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough district, but in fewer places compared to the previous week.
A red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
Last week, mean concentrations were reported in or off the coast of Pinellas County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory complaints continue to be reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No new respiratory problems have been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
